I grew up in Indiana and I am here to help you understand the dialect of these mysterious people.
Swole : Swollen
Eg: &ldquo;My whole foot was swole.&rdquo;
Busted : Fractured
Eg: &ldquo;He busted his arm.&rdquo;
Warsh : Wash
Eg: &ldquo;It&rsquo;s Friday, time to warsh yourself.&rdquo;
Ain&rsquo;t : That is certainly not true
Eg: &ldquo;Obama is a good leader.&rdquo; &ldquo;AIN&rsquo;T.&rdquo;
College : He lacks basic common sense because he is educated.
Eg: &ldquo;Wait, hay and straw are two different things?!&rdquo; &ldquo;[looks knowingly at another person] College.&rdquo;
Ma&rsquo;am : You are a woman who is even seven minutes older than me.
Eg: &ldquo;Hello my adult nephew who is in his forties. Can I take your coat?&rdquo; &ldquo;Yes ma&rsquo;am.&rdquo;
Pop : Carbonated non-alcoholic beverage.
Eg: &ldquo;Would you like some pop?&rdquo; &ldquo;You mean soda?&rdquo; &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t know what language you&rsquo;re speaking.&rdquo;
Hun : Patron of my establishment
Eg: &ldquo;Do you know what you want yet hun?&rdquo;
Them : The ; Them there : Those
Eg: &ldquo;It&rsquo;s them onions in them there taters that makes &rsquo;em taste so good.&rdquo;
Dinner : Lunch (if it&rsquo;s a big meal)
Eg: &ldquo;Dinner smells great grandma.&rdquo; &ldquo;Dinner?! We already had dinner! &hellip; sigh College.&rdquo;
Supper : Dinner
Eg: (continued) &ldquo;This if for supper, not dinner.&rdquo;
Musk Mellon : Cantaloupe
Eg: &ldquo;Mmm I love cantaloupe grandma!&rdquo; &ldquo;What? shakes head That&rsquo;s a musk mellon. &hellip; College.&rdquo;
The Race : The Indy 500
Eg: &ldquo;What are you doing for the race?&rdquo;
Parts : Region
Eg: &ldquo;He&rsquo;s not from these parts.&rdquo;
Ball : Basketball
Eg: &ldquo;You play ball?&rdquo;

