This is my oldest extant list. I made it in a text document maybe 10 years ago, then copied it to my iPhone notes app, then a new app I used for a while, then Evernote, and recently back to the (improved) iPhone notes app.
&ldquo;See how elastic our stiff prejudices grow when love once comes to bend them.&rdquo;
One of my favorite lines of all and one I&rsquo;ve deployed in many conversations.
&ldquo;Truly to enjoy bodily warmth, some small part of you must be cold, for there is no quality in this world that is not what it is merely by contrast.&rdquo;
Another favorite and one I tell myself often. To live is to feel in all its varieties.
&ldquo;The most reliable and useful courage is that which arises from the fair estimation of the encountered peril.&rdquo;
There&rsquo;s a lot of wisdom in that line I think.
&ldquo;A purse is but a rag unless you have something in it.&rdquo;
True true.
&ldquo;Any human thing supposed to be complete must for that very reason infallibly be faulty.&rdquo;
I&rsquo;m not sure I understand this line. Is it the human association that makes it faulty, or the supposed completeness? Is completeness a fault? The most important thing I get from this dusty line in my virtual notebook is that I should re-read Moby Dick.

