&ldquo;The galaxy is a really huge, flat disk, with the spiral arm pattern in it. Stars nearer the core orbit the center of the galaxy faster than ones farther out, and so you might expect the arms to wind up over time. But they don’t. That led astronomers to think of them like density waves, like traffic jams with stars instead of cars. A traffic jam isn’t a solid thing; cars enter it on one side, slow down, make their way through it, and leave on the other side. Over time, the jam is still there, but the individual cars come and go. That’s a density wave.&rdquo;
Phil Plait is good at this stuff.
Our Galaxy Just Got a Little More Interesting

Sophia is demonstrating the Maori &ldquo;Haka&rdquo; for her class today and I can&rsquo;t tell you how much I wish I could be there to watch.
How did this come to pass, you ask?
Sophia&rsquo;s friend Maia is doing her final research project on New Zealand. For their research projects they have to do a &ldquo;product&rdquo;, which is just some kind of model, poster, experiment, or demonstration related to their topic. The teacher suggested Maia could demonstrate the Haka for the class. Maia is a tad shy and said she couldn&rsquo;t possibly do it
The teacher said, &ldquo;You have a friend that I think would be happy to do it with you.&rdquo;
Sophia was thrilled. They practiced all afternoon yesterday and it was adorable. Maia will explain and Sophia will demonstrate. Sophia has the words and movements memorized, and she does it with real gusto, as those of you who know her can probably imagine. She told me, &ldquo;I&rsquo;m doing the boy version, because they get to make mean faces and slap their chests. The girls just ring bells for that part.&rdquo;

I just called in response to a &ldquo;suspicious activity&rdquo; email from Bank of America. The guy that answered was laughing and talking to someone else, then cleared his throat and said, &ldquo;uh, this is, uh, Bank of America [laughter], uh, can I get your credit card number please?&rdquo;
So I hung up assuming it was some scammer, called the main number, got routed to the fraud department, and it turns out that really was the Bank of America fraud security department, and I really did have suspicious activity.
Keepin&rsquo; it classy, bofa.

This is 100% true.
Sophia just asked me for the 400th time if she can have something she knows she can&rsquo;t have. So I said, &ldquo;Let me tell you a story.&rdquo;:
&ldquo;There was once a farmer who had a mule to pull his cart. One day, the mule stopped abruptly to sniff some grass, and the pots fell off the cart. The farmer looked the mule in the eye and said, &lsquo;That&rsquo;s one.&rsquo; The next day, the mule stopped abruptly to watch a squirrel and a basket fell off the cart, spilling its contents on the road. The farmer looked the mule in the eye and said, &lsquo;That&rsquo;s two.&rsquo; The next day, the mule stopped abruptly to nibble some flowers, and the wheel fell off the cart. Then the farmer whipped the mule.&rdquo;
Then I looked Sophia in the eye and said, &ldquo;That&rsquo;s one.&rdquo;
She giggled and said, &ldquo;let me tell YOU a story!&rdquo; and told me this old family-favorite joke:
&ldquo;A duck went into a grocery store and said, &lsquo;Do you have any duck food?&rsquo; The grocer said, &lsquo;No, this is a grocery store and we don&rsquo;t serve ducks. Go away.&rsquo; The next day the duck came in and said, &lsquo;Do you have any duck food?&rsquo; The grocer said, &lsquo;No! This is a grocery store. Now if you ask me again, I&rsquo;m going to nail your feet to the floor.&rsquo; The next day, the duck came in again and said, &lsquo;Do you have any nails?&rsquo; Exasperated, the grocer yelled, &lsquo;No! THIS IS A GROCERY STORE.&rsquo; Then the duck said, &lsquo;Do you have any duck food.&rsquo;&rdquo;
Then she looked ME in the eye and said, &ldquo;Do you have a whip?&rdquo;

